licence_overview:
To keep non-native crayfish, which are all crayfish other than the native or white clawed crayfish - Austropotamobius pallipes - you need a licence from the [Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (Defra)](http://www.defra.gov.uk/ "Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (Defra)"){:rel="external"} in England, the [Department for Rural Affairs](http://wales.gov.uk/topics/environmentcountryside/?lang=en "Department for Rural Affairs"){:rel="external") in Wales, the Scottish Government [Environment and Rural Affairs Department](http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Topics/Environment "Environment and Rural Affairs Department"){:rel="external"} in Scotland or the [Department of Agriculture and Rural Development (DARD)](http://www.dardni.gov.uk/ "Department of Agriculture and Rural Development (DARD)"){:rel="external"} in Northern Ireland.

This licence does not allow you to release or introduce any other species of non-native crayfish into the wild. To introduce or release non-native species into the wild you will require a licence issued under the [Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981.](http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1981/69 "Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981"){:rel="external"}

*[DARD]: Department of Agriculture and Rural Development
